<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
Three Sachems: Clay, Webster, Calhoun
---
By David Shribman</HL>
<DD> 11/09/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
   Three decades ago, John Kennedy, obsessed with greatness in Congress but unwilling to achieve it himself, headed a committee to select which senators to honor with portraits in the ornate Senate Reception Room. 
Scholars and commentators were consulted and the verdict was fairly predictable. 
The top three finishers were Henry Clay, Daniel Webster and John C. Calhoun. 

   Clay, Webster and Calhoun -- their names flow off the tongue in a group. 

   The leading political figures of the "second generation" of American leaders, they were, as University of Virginia historian Merrill Peterson puts it, "part of the furniture of American memory." 

   "The Great Triumvirate" (Oxford, 576 pages, $27.95) is an unusual alchemy -- one part history, one part biography -- by a leading American historian who argues that these three men -- one from the East, one from the South, one from the West -- were the match of the founding generation of Americans: "When the last of this 'second race of giants' passed away in 1852, nothing was left to challenge the sway of the Lilliputians," he writes. 
"The republic lost its glory -- the regalia of great statesmen." 

   Henry Clay, the man John Quincy Adams called "a republican of the first fire," elevated the House to new importance. 
He fashioned his own ideology, an "American System" that consisted of policies to encourage national economic development, chiefly protective tariffs and a series of internal improvements that now would be known as public-works projects. 
And though he thought slavery would wither away -- he later advocated repatriating slaves back to Africa as colonists -- he became known for his ability to sculpt compromise after compromise on the slavery question. 
Clay, according to Mr. Peterson, had a "genius for accommodation, sensitivity to opposing political forces and ingenuity in adapting old policies to new conditions." 

   Webster is known in history much the same way he was known as a young Boston lawyer with a gift for oratory -- the "guardian of the Constitution." 
Mr. Peterson credits him with pioneering the "theory of the Constitution as the fundamental law of one people, rather than a compact of sovereign states." 

   And John C. Calhoun. 
First pressed by the early Nullifiers, then their champion, he embraced this tool of expedience to assure his base in South Carolina, to protect his region from the threat of high tariffs and to muffle the drumbeats of Abolition. 
"It took possession of him, transfixed his political vision, and justified all his actions," says Mr. Peterson. 

   He once viewed slavery as scaffolding for the South, support that would be removed "when the building is finished." 
Later he came to call it "a great good." 
He was, moreover, a proponent of small government in the Jefferson model, aiming for nothing less, as he put it, "than to turn back the Government to where it commences operations in 1789." 
Mr. Peterson sees Calhoun's power resting "not on charisma or organization but on a political ideology that postulated unity in the state and eventually in the section as the only means of securing slavery and the South from an encroaching northern majority." 

   The three united in 1832 to oppose Andrew Jackson but, Mr. Peterson points out, spent most of their public lives dancing a political version of the country reel, changing partners and calculating their every move with an eye on what the others would do. 
Webster first opposed Clay on tariff protection, then switched sides and found himself opposing Calhoun. 
Calhoun, as vice president under John Quincy Adams, stacked the Senate Foreign Relations Committee against Secretary of State Clay. 
And although Clay and Webster, the two leading Whigs, united in opposing an independent Treasury scheme proffered by the Van Buren administration, they fought so much they paved the way for William Henry Harrison to snatch the presidency in 1840. 

   Each had great achievements. 
From his position in the border state of Kentucky, Clay formed two great compromises. 
Although he never shed the charges of "bargain and corruption" growing out of his maneuvers that left John Quincy Adams as president in 1824, he was an active and successful secretary of state. 
Webster is now regarded as among the greatest secretaries of state in history, having prevented war with the British and helped fix the nation's northern border. 
And Calhoun today is regarded as one of the few original thinkers of the era that followed the Founding Fathers'. 

   Despite the triumvirs' documented greatness, Mr. Peterson offers harsh assessments of their legacies. 
The Civil War that followed their deaths would have offered Clay "grim proofs of the limits of compromise." 
It would have demonstrated to Webster "the fragility of law and constitutions before moral and social forces he never truly understood." 
And it offered an "awful judgment" on Calhoun. 
His face ended up on the currency and postage stamps not of the U.S., but of the Confederacy. 

   ---
   Mr. Shribman is a reporter in the Journal's Washington bureau. 

</TEXT>
