<TEXT>
   ``Every man is said to have his peculiar ambition. Whether it be
true or not, I can say for one that I have no other so great as
that of being truly esteemed of my fellow man, by rendering myself
worthy of their esteem.'' _ Abraham Lincoln.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Abraham Lincoln received the Republican
Party's nomination for president in 1860, the New York Herald
dismissed him as a ``fourth-rate lecturer, who cannot speak good
grammar, and who, to raise the wind, delivers his hackneyed,
illiterate compositions at $200 apiece.''
   The man later compared to Mark Twain for his gift with the
English language was nicknamed Ignoramus Abe, Old Scoundrel and
Filthy Story-Teller.
   ``I have endured a great deal of ridicule without much malice
and received a great deal of kindness not quite free of ridicule,''
Lincoln once said, referring to the condescending treatment his
homespun style received even from friends.
   But historians have seen him differently, finding richness in
the language of a poor, country lawyer. The Library of America,
which has previously published the works of Twain, Henry James and
other celebrated writers, is honoring Lincoln with a two-volume,
$35 publication of his speeches and letters: ``Lincoln: Speeches
and Writings 1832-1858'' and ``Lincoln: Speeches and Writings
1859-1865.''
   ``How do we define literature?'' asked editor Don E.
Fehrenbacher, author of ``Lincoln in Text and Context: Collected
Essays,'' and ``The Dred Scott Case: Its Significance in American
Law and Politics,'' which won the Pulitzer Prize for history in
1979.
   ``He is able to write in such a way as to express deep emotion
under artistic control. That's what we look for in a (Ernest)
Hemingway or in a Henry James, and that's what we get in Lincoln's
best works.
   ``That combination of something fundamental to say that goes
beyond mere intellect. There is artistry in his letters, that ear
for the English language.''
   The author of the Gettysburg Address composed all his own
speeches despite spending only 12 months in school. He was part
philosopher, part politician, part poet. His influences included
Shakespeare, the King James version of the Bible and long-time
Speaker of the House Henry Clay, whose dealmaking earned him the
nickname ``The Great Compromiser.''
   Lincoln was a progressive pragmatist. He staked his political
career on opposition to slavery, but tempered that with assurances
that blacks would be better off living in their own country once
freed. ``I have no desire to own a slave or to marry one'' was how
he summed up his position.
   He first presented himself as lagging sadly behind _ a
reluctant, almost embarrassed public servant, more familiar with
the straight path back to his Kentucky log cabin on Nolan Creek
than the winding, uphill climb to the White House.
   In an open letter to the people of Illinois' Sangamon County,
published March 9, 1832, Lincoln offered sincere, cut-and-dry
analyses of local issues as he urged consideration for election to
the Illinois General Assembly and concluded with a near apology for
taking up the voters' time.
   He was born Feb. 12, 1809, the second child of pioneer farmer
and carpenter Thomas Lincoln and Nancy Hanks Lincoln. He was just 2
when his family moved out of the log cabin to a 230-acre farm on
Knob Creek, 11 miles northeast of Hodgenville, Ky.
   In his early 20s, after the family moved to Indiana and then to
Illinois, Lincoln made his home outside Decatur, Ill., and gave his
first known political speech in 1830, favoring improved navigation
on the Sangamon River.
   In 1834, a year after he was appointed postmaster of New Salem,
he was elected as a Whig to the Illinois House of Representatives
and served four terms. During that time, he received a license to
practice law and began his public opposition to slavery.
   ``The main routes upwards for men who were not well born were
law and politics,'' Fehrenbacher explained. ``There weren't that
many openings, and politics were much more central in those days.
The crowds came out and listened for hours.''
   Elected to Congress in 1846, Lincoln served just one term,
bitterly questioning President James K. Polk's use of troops in the
Mexican War. He left Washington after failing to receive an
appointment from the administration of President Zachary Taylor, a
fellow Whig.
   His life in politics seemingly over, Lincoln practiced law in
Springfield, where he lived with his wife, the former Mary Todd,
whom he married in 1842, and three sons, Robert Todd, Tad and
Willie (a fourth son, Edward, died at age 3).
   The slavery issue had apparantly been settled in 1820 when Clay
helped craft the Missouri Compromise, which allowed the South to
keep slaves but required abolition in a large section of
territories in the Midwest. The agreement, however, fell apart in
1854 when Congress passed the Kansas-Nebraska Act, which repealed
the anti-slavery language of the Missouri Compromise in favor of
``local sovereignty.''
   An enraged Lincoln, insisting that ``the spirit of '76'' and
``the spirit of Nebraska, are utter antagonisms,'' cut back on his
promising legal work and set his sights on the U.S. Senate.
   Thus was born the most famous political rivalry of the time:
Lincoln, the gangly, moody proponent of abolition, and Illinois
Sen. Stephen Douglas, the squat, gregarious author of the
Kansas-Nebraska Act and a powerful Northern Democrat.
   In 1856, Lincoln helped found the Republican Party of Illinois,
which opposed slavery. He warned two years later that ``a house
divided against itself cannot stand,'' anticipating that the United
States could not remain intact with conflicting laws.
   Fehrenbacher said the Lincoln-Douglas debates, included in their
entirety in the two-volume compilation, made Lincoln a national
figure.
   Thousands attended each of the seven confrontations, all held
outdoors, and frequently interrupted the speeches with loud
applause and cries of encouragement. The format was broken into
three parts: a one-hour opening statement, a 1{-hour reply and a
half-hour rejoinder.
   Slavery was virtually the only issue. Douglas made overtly
racist appeals and insisted the government was ``made for the
benefit of white men and their posterity for ever.''
   Said Lincoln:
   ``You say it must not be opposed in the free States, because
slavery is not here; it must not be opposed in the slaves States,
because it is there; it must not be opposed in politics, because
that will make a fuss; it must not be opposed in the pulpit,
because it is not religion. Then where is the place to oppose it?''
   Douglas won the election, but Lincoln was pleased enough with
the debates to have them published the following year.
   In the 1860 presidential campaign, with the Democrats badly
splintered, the election broke down into two regional campaigns:
Lincoln vs. Douglas in the North, and John C. Breckinridge vs. John
Bell in the South.
</TEXT>
