<HEAD>Snow In The Southeast - Already?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Brilliantly colored fall foliage was coated with snow and ice
Thursday in the mountains of North Carolina and frost headed as far
south as Alabama.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended during the afternoon over
North Carolina, South Carolina, northeastern Georgia, eastern
Tennessee and southwestern Virginia.
   The rain was mixed with snow in the Appalachians and changed
completely to snow at higher elevations.
   ``It was very pretty on these colored leaves,'' said Beulah
Calhoun at Calhoun Farm Supply in Newland, N.C.
   Elsewhere in North Carolina, 8 inches of snow accumulated at
Mount Mitchell and Mount Pisgah got a little more than an inch, the
National Weather Service reported. The National Park Service closed
two sections of the Blue Ridge Parkway in North Carolina because of
snow.
   ``I hear there is enough to scrape up a snowball,'' said Hugh
Morton at Grandfather Mountain.
   In eastern Tennessee, snow closed the Clingman Dome road in the
Great Smoky Mountains National Park, the weather service said.
   At lower elevations in North Carolina, thunderstorms produced
locally heavy rain at Charlotte, including 1.50 inches in the six
hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, and across much of Mecklenburg County,
flooding some streets and roads, the weather service said.
   Hail about an inch in diameter fell at Locust, N.C.
   A tornado warning was issued for part of eastern North Carolina
after a waterspout was spotted offshore. The waterspout, a tornado
that forms over water, did not come ashore.
   Cold air headed southward across the Ohio and Tennessee valleys
with temperatures expected to reach the low 30s by Friday morning
in northern Alabama, and the mid to upper 30s across central and
southern Alabama.
   Frost advisories were posted over much of Kentucky and frost
warnings were issued over southwestern Ohio. Advisories for frost
and freezing temperatures were posted over Indiana and southeastern
Lower Michigan.
   Elsewhere, rain was scattered over western New York state and
northeastern Ohio.
   Rain extended from north-central and western Washington state
into northwestern Oregon.
   Strong, gusty wind blew across the northern Pacific Coast during
the morning, with gusts reaching 44 mph at Astoria, Ore., 47 mph at
Bellingham, Wash., and 56 mph at Seaside, Ore.
   Thursday's low for the Lower 48 states was 19 degrees in
Gunnison, Colo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at Chippewa County Airport, Mich., to 96 degrees at Palm
Springs, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

