<HEAD>Did Abe Lincoln Visit Cape May?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to ADD that Monday is Lincoln's birthday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE MAY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven score and one year ago, the A.
Lincoln who visited this seashore town may have been just a grocer
from Philadelphia.
   But some residents continue to insist it was the future 16th
president who stayed in a hotel in this resort community on July
31, 1849.
   Those who dispute the tale say Lincoln, whose birthday comes
Monday, was in Springfield, Ill., practicing law that long-ago July
31, winning a judgment of $112.30 for a client. Casting further
doubt is a record of an Abel Lincoln, a Philadelphia grocer who
they say may have headed to the Jersey shore that summer day.
   ``All these years, we may have been honoring a grocer,'' said
Jake Schaad, who has researched the story and is writing a book
about the history of Cape May.
   One version of the story claims that, while in Cape May, Lincoln
rejected an offer to become governor of the Oregon Territory after
his wife, Mary Todd Lincoln, told him she was afraid of Indians,
Schaad said.
   ``It's a good story but it didn't happen,'' Schaad said, adding
that other versions have Lincoln fathering an illegitimate son
while at the shore.
   The town claims to be America's oldest seashore resort, tracing
its visitors to just after the Revolutionary War, said Jeffrey
Dorwart, a history professor at Rutgers University-Camden who is
researching a book for Cape May County's 300th anniversary in 1992.
   Some long-time residents knew Henry Irick, who said that when he
was 16 he came with his father and Lincoln to this community of
Victorian homes and lazy sea breezes.
   Mary Ann Nyblade, a 65-year-old Cape May resident who can trace
her family in the town back to 1695, said she still clings to
Irick's story.
   Irick was the son of John S. Irick, a wealthy Vincentown farmer
who supposedly met up with Lincoln and came to the Mansion House in
Cape May. He recalled that visit in a newspaper interview in the
late 1890s and the story was born, Ms. Nyblade said.
   The Mansion House guest register shows an A. Lincoln and wife
from Philadelphia in Room 24. Fire destroyed the hotel in 1856 but
the register was saved, Ms. Nyblade said. She acknowledged that the
reference to Philadelphia on the register was a problem for the
future-president theorists, but say the future president may have
listed Philadelphia if they had taken the steamboat from there to
Cape May.
   The man who saved that register was Lewis Stevens, and the
250-page book is now in Huntsville, Ala., in a safe-deposit box
owned by Bill Stevens, Ms. Nyblade's nephew and a descendant of
Lewis Stevens.
   Bill Stevens said in a telephone interview that the register
contains signatures of other famous people such as Sen. Henry Clay.
However, he said he has learned too much about Lincoln to believe
he could have visited Cape May.
   ``I'm convinced he was not in Cape May at that time,'' he said.
   There's no doubt about that, said Thomas F. Schwartz, curator of
the Lincoln collection at the Illinois State Historical Library in
Springfield.
   On July 31, Lincoln was at least 1,000 miles west of Cape May,
filing an affidavit in Sangamon County Circuit Court for Henry
Bailer, who was owed $111.75 by Oliver Davis. Davis ended up paying
$112.30, which Schwartz guesses included interest.
   Dorwart said he can prove President Benjamin Harrison spent
summers in Cape May, as did President U.S. Grant and Woodrow Wilson
while he was governor of New Jersey. But Lincoln is a different
story.
   ``My sense is that, since looking at the Lincoln papers, he was
in Illinois,'' Dorwart said.
   He said residents of Cape May, 50 miles south of the Mason-Dixon
Line and site of several duels between Northerners and Southerners
in the 1840s and 1850s, may have been trying to prove their loyalty
to the Union after the Civil War by circulating the story.
   Irick's tale probably cemented the story as fact, Dorwart said.
   The Cape May County Historical Museum still features a facsimile
of the hotel register signature and everybody acknowledges that
some legends just seem to die hard.
   ``Even if Lincoln didn't come down here, it's part of our
culture that he was here,'' Dorwart said.
</TEXT>
